default…We’ve got Sir Michael Wilshaw in Ofsted saying, “We’re going to inspect the local authorities and you are responsible for outcomes for all children, even if it’s in academie
defaults and free schools; it’s down to you to sort out how you negotiate that space with the academies”. We’ve got the DfE saying, “Actually schools are autonomous, they’re out of local authority control” (interview 11 April 2013).
defaultThis
default ambiguity
default has practical i
defaultmplications for 
defaultLAs when 
defaultrationalising services and
default managing
default their costs. For example, when discussing statutory provision of Governor Services in one case study LA I was told:  
defaultWe looked into this quite carefully and in fact we asked our legal department
default to look into exactly what the Local Authority was obliged to provide but it was not easy to discern. In the end the Local Authority believes that the induction training that we are providing for new Governors and new Chairs of Governors is something that 
defaultwe are obliged to provide (interview 16 April 2013).
defaultFor the main part,
default 
defaultthe case study 
defaultLAs seem to be minimising commitments to statutory provision
default,
default particularly in respect of academies
default. 
default 
defaultHowever, they are still engaged in a transitional situation. One res
defaultpondent drew attention to differences between sponsored and converter academies in relation to her LA’s responsibility for school improvement. She pointed out that the LA was likely to be already working with schools who were becoming sponsored academies, 
defaultand that the LA was taking the lead in supporting the conversion process. 
defaultT
defaulthe sponsor in my view should be wholly involved in the period up until conversion, and my experience is that they’re quite reluctant to do that.  Obviously they will do the TUPE
default a
defaultnd the statutory stuff that has to be done to keep the processes moving along, but in terms of school improvement, particularly in trying to raise achievement or trying to improve the quality of teaching, it’s quite difficult to get them involved until the
default actual co
defaultnversion date has taken place. 
defaultThat I don’t think is in the best interests of the school. 
default(Interview 16 May 2013)
defaultThis situation is further complicated because the sponsored academies are generally in a position where they are being ‘forced’ to c
defaultonvert. Schools dislike this situation, and so it seems do the LAs in my case studies. 
defaultWe’re pretty consistent there because one of the things that I don’t think anyone is comfortable with is this whole concept of forced academies. And we’ve had quite int
defaulteresting exchanges with the DfE about this, because they’ve come down with a hit list of schools and say, right this where you’ve g
defaultot to do this. I think issuing 
defaultwarning notices and things
default…
defaultBut our principle has always been that if a school is going to convert, unless it’s absolutely failing and it’s on its knees – and we don’t have schools like that in 
default[this LA]
default at the moment – then it’s something you negotiate with the governors. 
default(interview
default 11 April 2013)
defaultFurthermore, 
defaulta
default respondent suggested that sponsored
default ac
defaultademies were a threat to the LA
default maintaining a school improvement service, even as a traded service since “the more schools that are forced academies, I think they are less likely to buy b
defaultack because if you are a sponsored academy you will have your budget top-sliced by your sponsor for school improvement, so why would you then find another pot of money to buy local authority school improvement?” 
default(Interview 16 May 2013)
