defaultConclusionsdefaultThe LAs 
defaultreported in this study recognise their statutory responsibilities for disadvantaged children. However, recent structural reforms are impacting in various ways on their capacity to act upon these responsibilities. This research suggests that 
defaulta market econom
defaulty of schooling and services to schools impacts upon local authorities’ capacity to meet the needs of disadvantaged children and young people. LAs need the financial and human resources to respond to the issues that come to them. As inequalities within soci
defaultety increase, there will be greater demand placed upon LAs
default to respond to the needs of children.  
default&#xa0;
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultreported study i
defaultndicates that there remains a considerable lack of clarity around role and
default responsibility 
defaultin the interactions between 
defaultschools and local 
defaultauthorities
default 
defaultand also through external relations
defaulthips
default with governmental bodies such as Ofsted. While a simple solution to
default the
default ambiguity may appear to be more clearly de
defaultfining lines of accountability, 
defaultI 
defaultthink
default there is a deeper problem to be resolved
default. Current 
defaultpolicies impacting upon the education and care of children emphasise competition, including the academies programme, forcing schools and
default LAs to compete for custom
default. While three of the four case studies reported upon in this paper are attempting to mitigate 
defaultthe
default competitive 
defaultconditions, the evidence suggests that external pressures such as funding and central accountability 
defaultare 
defaultwork
defaulting
default against
default their attempts at
default co-operati
defaulton
default or
default supporting
default community 
defaultengagement
default (see Boyask, forthcoming for a more detailed account 
defaultof the research findings and conclusions)
